Subject: [PATCH] lv2 dirent.h: give DT_* placeholders distinct values

The LV2 dirent.h declares DT_FIFO, DT_CHR, DT_BLK, DT_SOCK, DT_WHT
all as the same DT_INVALID (0xff) sentinel, since the LV2 filesystem
does not expose those file types.  libstdc++ 12.x's
<filesystem/dir-common.h> has a switch statement that branches on
all eight DT_* values:

    switch (d.d_type) {
      case DT_BLK: ...
      case DT_CHR: ...
      case DT_FIFO: ...
      ...
    }

With the DT_INVALID aliasing these compile-time-equal values produce
"duplicate case value" errors and libstdc++ fails to build.

Give each placeholder a distinct dummy value outside the normal
d_type range (0xf1..0xf5) so the switch statement compiles cleanly.
Run-time no LV2 directory read ever produces these values, so the
case labels are never hit.

diff --git a/newlib/libc/sys/lv2/sys/dirent.h b/newlib/libc/sys/lv2/sys/dirent.h
--- a/newlib/libc/sys/lv2/sys/dirent.h
+++ b/newlib/libc/sys/lv2/sys/dirent.h
@@ -8,13 +8,17 @@

 #define DT_INVALID			0xff
 #define DT_UNKNOWN			0
-#define DT_FIFO				DT_INVALID
-#define DT_CHR				DT_INVALID
 #define DT_DIR				1
-#define DT_BLK				DT_INVALID
 #define DT_REG				2
 #define DT_LNK				3
-#define DT_SOCK				DT_INVALID
-#define DT_WHT				DT_INVALID
+/* Distinct dummy values for file types the LV2 filesystem does not
+ * report.  Kept outside the normal d_type range so no LV2 directory
+ * read produces them at runtime; the labels exist only so libstdc++
+ * and other consumers with switch-on-d_type code compile cleanly. */
+#define DT_FIFO				0xf1
+#define DT_CHR				0xf2
+#define DT_BLK				0xf3
+#define DT_SOCK				0xf4
+#define DT_WHT				0xf5

 #define dirfd(dp)			((dp)->dd_fd)
